('DOC-040', 'Renewal Playbook', 'Save Play: Executive Escalation Protocol for At-Risk Enterprise Accounts', 'West', 'Enterprise', 'ALL ACCOUNTS',
 '2026-06-05',
 'RENEWAL PLAYBOOK: Executive Escalation Protocol. Applicability: Any Enterprise account with renewal risk score >75 and ARR >$1.5M. Triggered by: INC-0001 impact, SLA breach, or competitive threat. Step 1 - Executive Sponsor Assignment: Within 48 hours of risk identification, assign a VP or C-level executive sponsor. For accounts >$3M ARR, CRO personal involvement required. Step 2 - Outreach Cadence: Executive sponsor calls customer C-suite within 5 business days. Acknowledge impact directly and personally. Do not delegate to account team. Step 3 - Listening Session: First call is 80% listening. Document customer concerns, business impact, and specific requirements for continued partnership. Step 4 - Custom Proposal: Within 10 business days, deliver a written proposal addressing each customer concern with specific commitments, timelines, and accountability. Step 5 - Follow-through: Weekly executive check-ins until renewal is secured. Measure: NPS at each touchpoint. Success criteria: Renewal signed within 30 days of proposal delivery.'),

('DOC-041', 'Renewal Playbook', 'Save Play: Service Credit and Commercial Concession Framework', 'West', 'Enterprise', 'ALL ACCOUNTS',
 '2026-06-06',
 'RENEWAL PLAYBOOK: Service Credit and Commercial Concessions. Context: Following INC-0001, multiple West Enterprise accounts are requesting credits and concessions. This playbook defines the approved framework. Tier 1 (Severity 1 impact, >$3M ARR): Up to 15% of monthly charges as credit, plus up to 5% renewal discount, plus enhanced SLA terms at no additional cost. Tier 2 (Severity 2 impact, $1.5M-$3M ARR): Up to 10% of monthly charges as credit, plus up to 3% renewal discount. Tier 3 (Severity 3 impact or <$1.5M ARR): Standard SLA credit per contract terms, no additional discount. Additional levers: (a) Extended payment terms (Net-60 to Net-90), (b) Free tier upgrade for 6 months, (c) Dedicated support engineer for 90 days at no cost, (d) Free professional services engagement (up to 40 hours). Approval authority: Tier 1 requires CRO approval, Tier 2 requires VP Sales approval, Tier 3 can be approved by Regional Director. Total INC-0001 credit exposure estimated at $2.1M across all affected accounts.'),

('DOC-042', 'Renewal Playbook', 'Save Play: Reliability Roadmap Review - Customer Presentation Template', 'West', 'Enterprise', 'ALL ACCOUNTS',
 '2026-06-07',
 'RENEWAL PLAYBOOK: Reliability Roadmap Customer Presentation. Purpose: Rebuild customer confidence by demonstrating concrete reliability investments post INC-0001. Target audience: Technical decision-makers (CTO, VP Eng) at West Enterprise accounts with renewal risk >70. Presentation structure: (1) Acknowledgment: "We fell short of your expectations. Here is exactly what happened and what we are doing about it." (2) Root Cause Transparency: Full technical explanation of INC-0001 (firmware defect, thermal conditions, blast radius). Customers respect honesty. (3) Immediate Actions Taken (completed): firmware patching, enhanced monitoring, thermal safeguards. (4) 30-Day Deliverables: rack diversity for all >$1M accounts, automated failover testing, customer-visible reliability dashboard. (5) 90-Day Deliverables: multi-AZ storage with synchronous replication, sub-2-minute failover, enhanced SLA options. (6) 180-Day Vision: zero-downtime architecture, chaos engineering program, customer reliability advisory board. Key message: "We are investing $XX million in reliability. You will see measurable improvement within 30 days." Customize dollar amount per customer tier.'),

('DOC-043', 'Renewal Playbook', 'Save Play: Success Plan Reset for Post-Incident Recovery', 'West', 'Enterprise', 'ALL ACCOUNTS',
 '2026-06-08',
 'RENEWAL PLAYBOOK: Success Plan Reset. When to use: After a major incident (like INC-0001) has damaged the customer relationship, the existing success plan is no longer aligned with customer priorities. A reset demonstrates responsiveness and customer-centricity. Process: (1) Acknowledge that previous success metrics and goals need revision in light of the incident. (2) Schedule a dedicated success plan reset session (separate from QBR) within 2 weeks of incident. (3) Co-create new success criteria with customer input. Common post-incident success metrics: uptime measurement (customer-visible dashboard), recovery time objective (RTO) demonstration, proactive communication cadence, quarterly reliability reviews. (4) Assign dedicated Customer Success Engineer (CSE) for 90 days - not a new person, but elevated engagement from existing CSE. (5) Weekly progress reports against new success plan for first 60 days, then biweekly. (6) 90-day checkpoint: formal review of whether confidence has been rebuilt. If not, escalate to executive team. (7) Document all commitments in writing with customer sign-off. Expected outcome: transform incident damage into deeper partnership through demonstrated accountability.'),

('DOC-044', 'Renewal Playbook', 'Save Play: Competitive Displacement Defense for West Enterprise', 'West', 'Enterprise', 'ALL ACCOUNTS',
 '2026-06-10',
 'RENEWAL PLAYBOOK: Competitive Displacement Defense. Context: Following INC-0001, at least 4 West Enterprise accounts have confirmed receiving or soliciting competitive proposals. This playbook provides defense strategies. Intelligence gathering: (1) Identify which competitors are engaged (signals: customer mentions specific features, asks about data portability, reduces consumption). (2) Assess switching barriers: data volume (>100TB = high barrier), custom integrations, trained users, embedded workflows. (3) Map customer decision timeline against renewal date. Defense tactics: (a) Total cost of migration analysis - present realistic migration costs including downtime, retraining, and integration rebuild. (b) Feature gap analysis vs competitor - highlight capabilities competitor lacks. (c) Acceleration offer - bring forward roadmap items that address customer concerns. (d) Executive alignment - match or exceed competitor executive engagement level. (e) Proof of improvement - offer free 30-day enhanced monitoring showing reliability improvements since INC-0001. Red flags requiring immediate CRO escalation: customer requests data export in bulk, reduces workload volume >20%, refuses meetings, or mentions specific competitor migration timeline.'),

('DOC-045', 'Renewal Playbook', 'Save Play: Multi-Year Commitment Incentive for At-Risk Renewals', 'West', 'Enterprise', 'ALL ACCOUNTS',
 '2026-06-12',
 'RENEWAL PLAYBOOK: Multi-Year Commitment Incentive. Applicability: West Enterprise accounts considering churn due to INC-0001 where relationship is salvageable (renewal probability >40%). Strategy: Convert flight risk into long-term commitment by offering compelling multi-year economics. Offer structure: (a) 1-year renewal at current rates with enhanced SLA: minimal incentive, signals lack of confidence in own platform. Not recommended. (b) 2-year renewal: 8% discount + enhanced SLA + dedicated support + quarterly executive reviews. Recommended for accounts with renewal risk 70-80. (c) 3-year renewal: 12% discount + premium SLA (99.99%) + dedicated compute option + named executive sponsor + annual innovation workshop. Recommended for accounts with renewal risk >80 where switching cost is high. Break-even analysis: 12% discount on a $3M account = $360K/year reduction. Cost of acquisition for replacement revenue = 18-24 months of effort. Multi-year lock-in provides $5.28M guaranteed vs risk of $0. Always present total contract value to customer to anchor on commitment size.'),

