('DOC-071', 'QBR Call Summary', 'Q2 QBR: GoldCoast Media - Advertiser SLA Discussion', 'West', 'Enterprise', 'GoldCoast Media',
 '2026-06-24',
 'Q2 2026 QBR with GoldCoast Media. Attendees: Customer - Director Ad Operations, CFO, Head of Engineering; Internal - Account Executive, Customer Success Manager, Solutions Architect. Critical meeting focused on $2M advertiser revenue clawback risk from INC-0001. Key outcomes: (1) Customer presented timeline showing their advertiser complaint and revenue risk. (2) We offered to provide formal incident documentation and reliability commitments that GoldCoast can share with their advertiser. (3) Customer requests: real-time SLA dashboard they can embed in their advertiser-facing portal, guaranteed campaign-window protection (no maintenance during declared campaign periods), and immediate notification (<2 min) of any service degradation. (4) Commercial ask: 20% discount on renewal citing $2M business impact. (5) Customer will not churn (strong technical fit) but will aggressively negotiate on price. Renewal probability: 75% at current terms, 95% with concessions. Contract: $1.3M ARR, renewal 2026-10-01. Renewal risk: 82/100.'),

('DOC-072', 'Support Case Note', 'CASE-89534: Pacific Mutual Insurance - Query Compilation Latency Update', 'West', 'Enterprise', 'Pacific Mutual Insurance',
 '2026-06-18',
 'Customer: Pacific Mutual Insurance. Follow-up to CASE-88745. Issue: Customer query compilation latency investigation complete. Findings: 2-3x compilation time increase during 8-10am window is caused by concurrent DDL operations from their new data pipeline (running CREATE OR REPLACE TABLE 400+ times per hour during that window). Recommended: switch to INSERT OVERWRITE pattern to eliminate DDL overhead. Customer engineering team implementing fix. Note: Customer initially attributed this to INC-0001 residual impact. After technical explanation, customer acknowledged this is organic growth issue unrelated to the incident. CIO appreciated transparent investigation. Positive interaction that slightly reduces renewal tension. Updated renewal risk: 84/100 (down from 87).'),

('DOC-073', 'Renewal Playbook', 'Save Play: 90-Day Reliability Proof Program', 'West', 'Enterprise', 'ALL ACCOUNTS',
 '2026-06-18',
 'RENEWAL PLAYBOOK: 90-Day Reliability Proof Program. Purpose: For accounts where renewal decision hinges on demonstrated reliability improvement, offer a structured 90-day proof program with measurable outcomes. Structure: (1) Day 1-7: Deploy enhanced monitoring on customer workloads with customer-visible dashboard showing real-time uptime, latency p50/p95/p99, error rates. (2) Day 1-30: Weekly reliability report emailed to customer executive sponsor showing all metrics trending. (3) Day 30: First checkpoint - present 30-day reliability data. Target: 99.99%+ uptime, <100ms p95 latency, <0.01% error rate. (4) Day 31-60: Conduct chaos engineering exercise (controlled failover test) with customer observation. Demonstrate recovery in <2 minutes. (5) Day 60: Second checkpoint - present 60-day data plus chaos test results. (6) Day 61-90: Customer validates via their own monitoring that metrics are sustained. (7) Day 90: Final review - data-driven renewal conversation. Target accounts: Any West Enterprise account with renewal >60 days out and risk 70-85. Accounts with <60 days need faster intervention (see Executive Escalation playbook). Expected impact: 40% reduction in renewal risk score for participating accounts.'),

